2	// evidence/browser/observe.js - the PECR pre-consent OBSERVATION lane (P3 Wave-1c).
3	//
4	// WHAT THIS SEES THAT HTML CANNOT (caution.md C-039): the PECR reg.6 breach is not in the page
5	// source, it is in BEHAVIOUR - non-essential cookies written, and tracker requests fired, on first
6	// load with NOTHING clicked. This lane loads a page in a fresh browser, touches nothing, records the
7	// cookies + tracker network events that appear BEFORE any consent interaction, then accepts consent
8	// and captures again for the pre/post diff. A non-essential cookie/tracker present pre-consent is an
9	// observed breach candidate carrying the captured network event as its deterministic artifact
10	// (Constitution Rule 3). This module only OBSERVES; the breach lane (P3 Wave 2) adjudicates.
11	//
12	// FOUR structural safeguards this file is built around:
13	//   1. DEADLINE (C-040 / Rule 9): ONE outer Promise.race wraps launch -> observe -> close. The 752s
14	//      hostage incident is structurally impossible here: observe() cannot outlast deadlineMs + a
15	//      bounded force-close, whatever the browser does. Proven by observe.test.js's hanging-fake test
16	//      and the p3-browser-deadline calibration fixture.
17	//   2. OPTIONAL DEPENDENCY (C-041): Playwright is NOT a package.json dependency. It is resolved
18	//      lazily via an injected launchBrowser factory (or the lazy adapter). When unavailable, the lane
19	//      records lane:{ran:false, reason:'playwright-unavailable'} LOUDLY - never a silent nothing,
20	//      never a throw that kills a mint.
